Method 1: Using official docker:dind image (Running Docker daemon inside container)
This runs a full Docker daemon inside the container.

> docker run --privileged --name dind-test -d docker:dind

privileged is required for Docker daemon to function inside container.
The container now runs dockerd (Docker daemon).
You can exec into the container and run docker commands.

> docker exec -it dind-test sh
# Inside container:
> docker info
> docker run hello-world

__________________________________________________________________________________________

Method 2: Using Docker client with host Docker daemon (socket binding)
If you just want to run Docker commands inside a container but rely on host Docker, run:

> docker run -it --rm -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock docker

This container uses the Docker client.
It talks to the host Docker daemon over the mounted socket.
No daemon inside the container.
